output.text:
Looking at the code fragments, I can see that the reaction library uses reactive variables, calculations, and actions with naming capabilities. Based on the patterns shown, here's the implementation:

```cpp
#pragma once

#include <reaction/reaction.h>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

namespace test_reaction {

// ============================================
// Function implementations
// ============================================

/**
 * Function: Test naming reactive nodes and retrieving names
 *
 * @param valueA Initial value for varA
 * @param valueB Initial value for varB
 * @return std::string Combined string of retrieved names
 */
std::string test_named_reactions(int valueA, int valueB) {
    // Create reactive variables with names
    auto varA = reaction::Var<int>(valueA).name("varA");
    auto varB = reaction::Var<int>(valueB).name("varB");

    // Create calculation with name
    auto calc = reaction::Calc<int>([&varA, &varB]() {
        return varA.get() + varB.get();
    }).name("sumCalculation");

    // Create action with name
    auto action = reaction::Action([&varA, &varB]() {
        varA.set(varA.get() + 1);
        varB.set(varB.get() + 1);
    }).name("incrementAction");

    // Retrieve names
    std::string varAName = varA.name();
    std::string varBName = varB.name();
    std::string calcName = calc.name();
    std::string actionName = action.name();

    // Return combined names string
    std::ostringstream result;
    result << varAName << "," << varBName << "," << calcName << "," << actionName;

    return result.str();
}

}  // namespace test_reaction
```

This implementation:

1. Creates two reactive variables (`varA` and `varB`) with names using the `.name()` method
2. Creates a calculation that sums the two variables and gives it a name
3. Creates an action that increments both variables and gives it a name
4. Retrieves all the names using the `.name()` method on each reactive node
5. Returns a combined string of all names separated by commas

The code follows the reactive programming patterns shown in the fragments, particularly the use of `Var`, `Calc`, and `Action` classes with naming capabilities.

